{'entities': [{'id': 40610, 'name': 'TiKV', 'description': 'TiKV is a distributed, transactional key-value database that powers TiDB. It handles the storage layer of the TiDB architecture, ensuring data availability and consistency across multiple nodes. One of its critical functionalities is leader balancing, which optimizes load distribution after node restarts or cluster changes. In TiDB v6.0.0, this process was enhanced with concurrency controls to significantly reduce rebalancing time, improving cluster stability and performance.'}, {'id': 40596, 'name': 'Leader Balancing', 'description': 'The process of redistributing Raft leaders across TiKV nodes for load balancing.'}, {'id': 810019, 'name': 'TiKV', 'description': 'TiKV is a distributed transactional key-value storage engine serving as the foundational layer for TiDB, a distributed SQL database. It uses RocksDB for local storage and Raft for replication, ensuring data consistency through log replication. Features include batch split support, row count-based region splitting, expression pushdowns including string, aggregation, encryption, and cast functions, and support for both optimistic and pessimistic transactions. TiKV dynamically adjusts resource quotas, handles backup/restore operations, supports encryption using AES or SM4, and can operate as a standalone key-value store (RawKV) without TiDB. It is used in TiDB Cloud and self-hosted platforms, deployable with or without TiFlash. Sufficient resources are recommended for optimal performance, and disk sharing is not advised. TiKV is scalable in the Dedicated Tier on AWS for clusters created post-December 31, 2022. Additionally, TiKV introduces Region Merge, Raw DeleteRange API, and improved read performance using ReadPool.'}, {'id': 93827, 'name': 'Data Migration', 'description': 'The process of moving data between TiKV nodes during scaling operations.'}, {'id': 30280, 'name': 'High TiKV resource usage', 'description': 'A scenario where TiKV consumes a significant amount of resources, nearing bottleneck threshold.'}, {'id': 30277, 'name': 'Scale-out', 'description': 'The process of adding more nodes to a cluster to increase capacity or performance.'}, {'id': 36982, 'name': 'Scale out TiKV', 'description': 'Adding more TiKV instances to the cluster.'}, {'id': 36966, 'name': 'Single TiKV thread bottleneck', 'description': 'A performance issue where a single thread in TiKV limits the overall throughput.'}, {'id': 1838, 'name': 'Scale-in Operation', 'description': "The process of removing nodes from a TiDB cluster. This can be achieved through various methods, including using TiUP or manually removing a node.  Successful scale-in results in the node's status becoming 'Tombstone'."}, {'id': 660151, 'name': 'TiDB Cluster', 'description': "A distributed NewSQL database system designed for high availability, scalability, and disaster recovery. It is compatible with MySQL and supports various deployment options including cloud-based (TiDB Cloud Serverless, TiDB Cloud Dedicated) and self-managed solutions. The cluster consists of several core components such as TiDB, TiKV, PD, TiFlash, TiProxy, Prometheus, Grafana, TiCDC, Pump, Drainer, TiKV Importer, and TiDB Lightning. Communication between components is secured via TLS encryption, and data restoration can be performed using full backups combined with binlog backups through the Reparo tool. Monitoring and diagnostics are facilitated by tools like Grafana + Prometheus and commands such as 'tiup diag collect ${cluster-name}'. The cluster supports high availability, strong consistency, horizontal scalability, and bidirectional replication via TiCDC. It can be managed using TiUP, TiDB Operator, or Terraform for deployment, scaling, and maintenance. The system is often used as a target database for applications and data migration from MySQL."}, {'id': 93795, 'name': 'MaxReplicas', 'description': "A parameter in the PD configuration that determines the maximum number of replicas for a TiKV store. When the number of 'UP' stores is equal to or less than MaxReplicas, TiKV components cannot be scaled in."}, {'id': 93841, 'name': 'EKS Node Group', 'description': 'A group of nodes within an EKS cluster.'}, {'id': 94161, 'name': 'Horizontal Scaling', 'description': 'Scaling TiDB, TiKV, and PD nodes horizontally.'}, {'id': 93526, 'name': 'Node Replacement/Upgrade', 'description': 'The process of replacing or upgrading nodes in a TiDB cluster, which can involve changing to higher configurations, newer Kubernetes versions, or other upgrades while ensuring no downtime. This process can involve creating a new node group and migrating the TiDB cluster via rolling restart.'}, {'id': 92353, 'name': 'Scaling in', 'description': 'The process of reducing the number of replicas in a deployment.'}, {'id': 93725, 'name': 'Scaling in PD Nodes', 'description': 'The process of removing PD nodes from a TiDB cluster.'}, {'id': 720120, 'name': 'TiUP', 'description': "TiUP is a comprehensive command-line tool and component manager for the TiDB ecosystem, designed to simplify the deployment, management, and upgrading of TiDB clusters and related components. It supports a wide range of tasks including deploying, starting, stopping, scaling, upgrading, and configuring TiDB clusters, as well as managing components like TiDB, PD, TiKV, TiFlash, and monitoring tools such as Prometheus and Grafana. TiUP facilitates both online and offline deployment methods, automates SSH mutual trust and passwordless login setup, and integrates functionalities for monitoring and alerting. It is the recommended tool for production environments, offering alternatives like TiDB Operator on Kubernetes and TiDB Ansible. TiUP utilizes a topology file to define and manage the desired state of the cluster, supports various TiDB versions, and provides a package management system to streamline the usage of TiDB ecosystem tools. Additionally, TiUP automatically creates the 'tidb' user on target machines and manages deployment directories."}], 'relationships': [{'id': 38935, 'relationship': 'Leader balancing is performed across TiKV nodes.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/release-6.0.0-dmr', 'source_entity': {'id': 40610, 'name': 'TiKV'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 40596, 'name': 'Leader Balancing'}}, {'id': 95289, 'relationship': 'Scaling TiKV involves data migration between nodes.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb-in-kubernetes/v1.6/scale-a-tidb-cluster', 'source_entity': {'id': 810019, 'name': 'TiKV'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 93827, 'name': 'Data Migration'}}, {'id': 30225, 'relationship': 'Scaling out TiKV is recommended to address high TiKV resource usage.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/performance-tuning-methods', 'source_entity': {'id': 30280, 'name': 'High TiKV resource usage'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 30277, 'name': 'Scale-out'}}, {'id': 35934, 'relationship': 'Scaling out TiKV can resolve single thread bottlenecks.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/troubleshoot-cpu-issues', 'source_entity': {'id': 36982, 'name': 'Scale out TiKV'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 36966, 'name': 'Single TiKV thread bottleneck'}}, {'id': 1456, 'relationship': 'A scale-in operation removes nodes from a TiDB cluster.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb/v8.1/scale-tidb-using-tiup', 'source_entity': {'id': 1838, 'name': 'Scale-in Operation'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 660151, 'name': 'TiDB Cluster'}}, {'id': 95253, 'relationship': "TiKV cannot be scaled in when the number of 'UP' stores is equal to or less than `MaxReplicas`.", 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb-in-kubernetes/v1.6/scale-a-tidb-cluster', 'source_entity': {'id': 810019, 'name': 'TiKV'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 93795, 'name': 'MaxReplicas'}}, {'id': 95295, 'relationship': 'Scaling out TiKV requires scaling out the corresponding EKS node groups.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb-in-kubernetes/v1.6/deploy-on-aws-eks', 'source_entity': {'id': 810019, 'name': 'TiKV'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 93841, 'name': 'EKS Node Group'}}, {'id': 95610, 'relationship': 'Horizontal scaling is performed for TiDB, TiKV, and PD nodes during replacement.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb-in-kubernetes/v1.6/replace-nodes-for-local-disk', 'source_entity': {'id': 94161, 'name': 'Horizontal Scaling'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 93526, 'name': 'Node Replacement/Upgrade'}}, {'id': 93729, 'relationship': 'Scaling in operations on TidbClusters can be controlled by the Advanced StatefulSet Controller.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb-in-kubernetes/v1.6/advanced-statefulset', 'source_entity': {'id': 92353, 'name': 'Scaling in'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 660151, 'name': 'TiDB Cluster'}}, {'id': 95161, 'relationship': 'Scaling in PD Nodes can be done using TiUP if the source cluster was deployed with it.', 'doc_link': 'https://docs.pingcap.com/tidb-in-kubernetes/v1.6/migrate-tidb-to-kubernetes', 'source_entity': {'id': 93725, 'name': 'Scaling in PD Nodes'}, 'target_entity': {'id': 720120, 'name': 'TiUP'}}]}

