{'entities': [{'id': 36383, 'name': 'PD Leader Election', 'description': 'The process of electing a new leader in a PD cluster. This process can be slow or fail due to various reasons.'}, {'id': 36384, 'name': 'region storage', 'description': "A feature in PD v3.0 that can significantly reduce region loading duration. It can be enabled by setting the 'use-region-storage' parameter to 'true'."}, {'id': 360473, 'name': 'PD Leader Switch', 'description': 'The PD Leader Switch is the process of changing the leader node in the Placement Driver (PD) cluster of TiDB. This process can trigger SQL execution errors due to a TiKV bug, cause restoration failures in Backup & Restore (BR), and may lead to region health data deletion. It is a critical process within the PD cluster.'}, {'id': 40955, 'name': 'Region Health monitoring data', 'description': 'Data used for monitoring the health of Regions in PD.'}, {'id': 50470, 'name': 'PD Leader Switching', 'description': 'The process of changing the primary node responsible for managing the TiKV cluster metadata.'}, {'id': 50473, 'name': 'use-region-storage', 'description': 'A feature in PD that stores Region Meta information on local LevelDB.'}, {'id': 36379, 'name': 'PD Leader Switches', 'description': 'The process of changing the leader node in a PD cluster. This can be caused by disk I/O load, network issues, or high system load.'}, {'id': 36382, 'name': 'High System Load on PD Node', 'description': "A condition where the PD node is under heavy system load. This can cause PD leader switches and can be indicated by the message 'server is likely overloaded'."}, {'id': 720294, 'name': 'pd', 'description': 'The Placement Driver (PD) is a critical component in the TiDB ecosystem, responsible for managing cluster metadata, data placement, scheduling, and ensuring high availability and fault tolerance. It verifies the identity of callers like TiDB using certificate-based authentication, with configurations such as `cert-allowed-cn` currently limited to a single value. PD manages cluster topology, leader election for TiKV, and stores metadata in etcd. It optimizes hot region scheduling, coordinates load balancing, and interacts with TiKV and TiDB components. PD provides essential services like TSO (Timestamp Oracle) allocation, supports TLS, various scheduling policies, and can be monitored using tools like pd-ctl. It is crucial for maintaining cluster health, addressing issues like hot regions and connection failures, and is accessed by components such as BR and TiCDC. PD can be deployed in microservice mode from v8.0.0 (experimental) and is configurable via the TidbCluster Custom Resource.'}, {'id': 690035, 'name': 'Leader Transfer', 'description': 'The process of transferring leadership within a distributed system, such as TiDB. This involves changing the designated leader node or the leader of a Region to another replica. The transfer can occur between data centers and is utilized during automated processes like rolling updates. It may trigger writing in-memory pessimistic locks to disk and replication to other replicas, while also avoiding newly created peers to reduce potential delays.'}, {'id': 362888, 'name': 'Placement Driver (PD)', 'description': "The Placement Driver (PD) is a core component of the TiDB cluster responsible for managing the cluster's metadata, scheduling tasks, and balancing data distribution across the cluster. It ensures high availability and optimizes the scheduling of Region Leaders to different physical nodes to evenly distribute read and write pressure. PD handles timestamp allocation, region scheduling, and data placement, ensuring data consistency and optimizing system availability using TiKV labels and placement rules. It features modules for managing cluster state, data recovery, and hot region management. PD supports high availability with a recommended deployment of at least three nodes and provides functionalities like manual leader changes, cross-data center scheduling, and a TiDB Dashboard UI. Recent improvements include bug fixes for issues like incorrect scaling progress display, leader transfer failures, and safepoint management during log backup tasks. PD is evolving towards splitting TSO and scheduling modules into independent microservices to reduce interference and support larger workloads."}, {'id': 900282, 'name': 'Region Leader', 'description': "The Region Leader is the primary replica within a Raft Group responsible for handling write requests and coordinating read operations. It executes both read and write tasks, replicates data to followers, and ensures consistent reads from follower replicas. The leader's responsibilities include managing write requests, replicating data, and coordinating Follower Read operations. While it can become a bottleneck under high read loads, its role is crucial for maintaining data consistency and availability within the Raft Group."}, {'id': 42833, 'name': 'watch leader', 'description': 'A functionality in PD that monitors the leader of the cluster.'}, {'id': 35253, 'name': 'Active PD Follower', 'description': "An experimental feature introduced in TiDB 7.6.0 designed to enhance the scalability of PD's region information query service. It distributes requests to all PD servers, including followers, aiming to reduce CPU load on the PD leader, especially beneficial in clusters with numerous TiDB nodes and Regions. This feature allows PD followers to handle Region information queries like GetRegion and ScanRegions.  It is controlled by the system variable `pd_enable_follower_handle_region`. However, as an experimental feature, it has potential bugs and is subject to change without notice.  Disconnected region synchronization streams or outdated region information from a follower will cause TiDB to retry the request with the PD leader."}, {'id': 420258, 'name': 'pd_enable_follower_handle_region', 'description': 'A system variable introduced in TiDB 7.6.0 that controls whether t